from plotnine import *
import geopandas as gpd
import pandas as pd

# Load world map from an online GeoJSON file
world = gpd.read_file("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/datasets/geo-countries/master/data/countries.geojson")

print(world.columns)
print(combined.columns)

# Merge on country names
map_data = pd.merge(world, combined, left_on='name', right_on='Country', how='left')

# Global Situation: Mother to child HIV Transmission Rates

  • The world map visualization reveals that Mother-to-child HIV transmission rates are predominantly higher across African nations.
  • This geographic concentration aligns closely with the disparities in healthcare infrastructure, economic development, and broader social determinants of health in these regions.
  • Limited access to quality maternal healthcare services, lower GDP per capita, and higher birth rates likely contribute to the elevated transmission rates observed.italicised text italicised text
Code 
#HIV rates by country
(ggplot(map_data) +
 aes(map_id='name', fill='HIV_Transmission') +  # map_id specified within aes()
 geom_map(color='white', size=0.2) +  # Removed map=map_data
 scale_fill_cmap(cmap_name='Reds', na_value='lightgrey') +
 theme_void() +
 labs(title='Mother-to-child HIV Transmission Rate by Country',
      fill='HIV Transmission (%)'))
Code 
# Merge datasets on BOTH "Country" and "Year"
combined = pd.merge(df2, df_meta, on=['Country', 'Year'], how='left')

# Average HIV Transmission rate globally per year
hiv_time = combined.groupby('Year')['HIV_Transmission'].mean().reset_index()

Top 10 Countries with Highest Transmission

The bar chart highlights the countries with the highest average Mother-to-child HIV transmission rates. Notably, many of these countries are located within sub-Saharan Africa, further reinforcing the regional disparities seen in the world map. These nations typically face systemic healthcare challenges, including limited prenatal care and lack of access to antiretroviral therapy for pregnant women, which are critical to preventing transmission.

 ))

Global HIV Transmission Over Time

The time series plot demonstrates a gradual decline in the average global Mother-to-child HIV transmission rates over the years. This trend suggests that global interventions â such as improved prenatal screening, increased availability of antiretroviral treatments, and awareness campaigns â have been effective. However, the pace of decline may vary significantly between regions, indicating that some countries still require targeted support and investment.

Code 
#HIV rates changing globally over years
(ggplot(hiv_time) +
 aes(x='Year', y='HIV_Transmission') +
 geom_line(color='blue') +
 geom_point(color='red') +
 labs(title='Global HIV Transmission Over Time',
      x='Year', y='Mother-to-child HIV Transmission Rate (%)') +
 theme_minimal())

HIV Transmission vs GDP per Capita

The scatterplot between HIV transmission rates and GDP per capita illustrates a clear negative correlation. Countries with higher GDP per capita generally experience lower Mother-to-child HIV transmission rates. This relationship emphasizes the role of economic stability in improving healthcare outcomes, with wealthier nations being better equipped to invest in maternal healthcare and HIV prevention programs.

Code 
#HIV vs GDP per Capita
(ggplot(combined) +
 aes(x='GDP_per_Capita', y='HIV_Transmission') +
 geom_point(color='purple', alpha=0.6) +
 stat_smooth(method='lm', color='orange') +
 labs(title='HIV Transmission vs GDP per Capita',
      x='GDP per Capita (US$)', y='Mother-to-child HIV Transmission Rate (%)') +
 theme_minimal())

HIV Transmission vs Life Expectancy

The scatterplot comparing HIV transmission rates and life expectancy indicates a negative association: Countries with higher life expectancy tend to have lower rates of Mother-to-child HIV transmission. This finding reinforces the idea that stronger healthcare systems, which contribute to longer average lifespans, also facilitate better maternal and infant health outcomes.

Healthier countries = fewer transmissions

Code 
#HIV vs Life Expectancy
(ggplot(combined) +
 aes(x='Life_Expectancy', y='HIV_Transmission') +
 geom_point(color='green', alpha=0.6) +
 stat_smooth(method='lm', color='black') +
 labs(title='HIV Transmission vs Life Expectancy',
      x='Life Expectancy (Years)', y='Mother-to-child HIV Transmission Rate (%)') +
 theme_minimal())

HIV Transmission vs Birth Rate

The scatterplot of HIV transmission rates against birth rates reveals a positive correlation: Countries with higher birth rates often exhibit higher Mother-to-child HIV transmission rates. High birth rates, combined with limited maternal healthcare resources, can increase the risk of transmission. This suggests that family planning, maternal health programs, and healthcare education should be integral parts of HIV prevention strategies.

Higher births + low healthcare = more HIV risk

Code 
#HIV vs Birth Rate
(ggplot(combined) +
 aes(x='Birth_Rate', y='HIV_Transmission') +
 geom_point(color='red', alpha=0.6) +
 stat_smooth(method='lm', color='blue') +
 labs(title='HIV Transmission vs Birth Rate',
      x='Birth Rate (per 1000 people)', y='Mother-to-child HIV Transmission Rate (%)') +
 theme_minimal())

Conclusion

This report analyzed Mother-to-child HIV transmission rates across countries, drawing on key global health and socioeconomic indicators.

The world map visualization clearly highlighted that African countries experience significantly higher transmission rates, reflecting disparities in healthcare infrastructure, access to medical services, and overall economic development.

Time series analysis revealed encouraging global progress, with a gradual decline in transmission rates over recent years â a positive result of international efforts to improve maternal health services and expand access to antiretroviral therapies.

Further, the strong negative correlations observed between HIV transmission rates and both GDP per capita and life expectancy reaffirm the critical role that economic stability and healthcare quality play in combating the epidemic. Meanwhile, the positive association between birth rate and HIV transmission emphasizes the importance of integrating maternal health education and family planning initiatives into national healthcare strategies.

Overall, while notable progress has been made, the data underscores the urgent need for sustained, targeted interventions â especially in low-income and high birth rate regions â to further reduce and ultimately eliminate Mother-to-child HIV transmission worldwide.
